,(6285,230,'position','player'),(6286,230,'_position','field_5383fd410a0b4'),(6287,218,'position','player'),(6288,218,'_position','field_5383fd410a0b4'),(6289,696,'position','player'),(6290,696,'_position','field_5383fd410a0b4'),(6291,729,'_edit_lock','1443041825:7'),(6292,729,'_edit_last','7'),(6293,731,'_wp_attached_file','2014/05/andySarouhan_236x236.jpg'),(6294,731,'_wp_attachment_metadata','a:5:{s:5:\"width\";i:236;s:6:\"height\";i:236;s:4:\"file\";s:32:\"2014/05/andySarouhan_236x236.jpg\";s:5:\"sizes\";a:1:{s:9:\"thumbnail\";a:4:{s:4:\"file\";s:32:\"andySarouhan_236x236-150x150.jpg\";s:5:\"width\";i:150;s:6:\"height\";i:150;s:9:\"mime-type\";s:10:\"image/jpeg\";}}s:10:\"image_meta\";a:10:{s:8:\"aperture\";i:0;s:6:\"credit\";s:0:\"\";s:6:\"camera\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"caption\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"created_timestamp\";i:0;s:9:\"copyright\";s:0:\"\";s:12:\"focal_length\";i:0;s:3:\"iso\";i:0;s:13:\"shutter_speed\";i:0;s:5:\"title\";s:0:\"\";}}'),(6295,729,'_thumbnail_id','731'),(6296,729,'extra_image_1',''),(6297,729,'_extra_image_1','field_52f273e29b5db'),(6298,729,'extra_image_2',''),(6299,729,'_extra_image_2','field_52f27616cf901'),(6300,729,'extra_image_3',''),(6301,729,'_extra_image_3','field_52f27626cf902'),(6302,729,'position','player'),(6303,729,'_position','field_5383fd410a0b4'),(6304,729,'sidebar','school-set-five'),(6305,729,'_sidebar','field_5380e7f58e3e8'),(6306,729,'right_column','<h1>Q &amp; A</h1>\r\n<p><strong>What do you like about improv?<br /></strong>I love improvisation because in order to do it, I must offer my complete attention to the activity. This sort of total engagement feels more life-like than anything I know.</p>\r\n<p><strong>What was your first BATS Show?<br /></strong>About 10 years ago I took a six-month intensive class with BATS Improv to train in narrative longform. The training resulted in a couple weekends of narrative longform shows entitled \"A Night of All Genres.\" There was definitely a story about a group of clowns gone bad.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Your first improv class?<br /></strong>On my high school improvisation team, the H.I.T. Squad, our fantastic drama teacher Vonya Morris helped to train us at lunch. I definitely remember an occasion where we had a coach from BATS Improv come down for a special workshop.</p>\r\n<p><strong>What are your favorite formats?<br /></strong>I\'m a sucker for Spontaneous Broadway or a longform musical. I also enjoy shows that are shortform scenes in the first act and a longform story in the second act. The Un-Scripted Theater Company has a show called \"Act I, Scene II\" in which they have a playwright provide the first scene of an incomplete play. The improvisers read out the first scene in front of an audience, and wherever the script ends, the improvisers create the remainder of the play on the spot. It\'s amazing work.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Best moment on the BATS stage?<br /></strong>Once in a longform show, I happened to be playing both a homicidal clown and a dead-beat dad, and the climax of the show was the clown shooting the dad. I had to run back and forth across the stage to shoot the rifle, then take the bullet, then do the reactions of both characters.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Why should people study improv?<br /></strong>Improvisation has taught me that the quality of my life is based upon attention. Like other intense activities such as sports, meditation, or even great conversation, improvisation invites me to strengthen and direct my capacity to be present.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Any improv advice?<br /></strong>Let the humor find the scene, rather than you imposing humor on the scene.</p>\r\n<p><strong>What are your artistic influences?<br /></strong>I read a lot: novels, nonfiction, and philosophy. I sometimes feel that if my job as an improviser is to bring my full self to a spontaneous performance, then maybe the best thing I can do is to fill myself up with a wide spectrum of stuff. I\'d also say that the larger San Francisco improvisation community is a major artistic influence -- it\'s an inspiring place to be an improviser because the community respects both artistry and entertainment.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Favorite movies?<br /></strong><em>Children of Men. Bamboozled. Kill Bill I &amp; II. The Exorcist. 300. Bullworth. A Streetcar Named Desire. No Country for Old Men. True Grit. Easy Rider. </em>(Apparently I like violent movies!!!)</p>\r\n<p><strong>Favorite music?<br /></strong>Bob Marley. Andrew Bird. Keith Jarrett. Flaming Lips. Manu Chao. Babatunde Olatunji. Crosby, Stills, Nash, &amp; Young. Grateful Dead. Fleet Foxes.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Favorite play?<br /></strong><em>Angels in America</em> (This opinion hasn\'t changed since the first time I read it when I was like 19.)</p>'),(6307,729,'_right_column','field_52f276e1f1ba0'),(6308,732,'_edit_lock','1416714547:4'),(6309,732,'_edit_last','4'),(6310,733,'_wp_attached_file','2014/05/patriciaPearson_236x236.jpg'),(6311,733,'_wp_attachment_metadata','a:5:{s:5:\"width\";i:236;s:6:\"height\";i:236;s:4:\"file\";s:35:\"2014/05/patriciaPearson_236x236.jpg\";s:5:\"sizes\";a:1:{s:9:\"thumbnail\";a:4:{s:4:\"file\";s:35:\"patriciaPearson_236x236-150x150.jpg\";s:5:\"width\";i:150;s:6:\"height\";i:150;s:9:\"mime-type\";s:10:\"image/jpeg\";}}s:10:\"image_meta\";a:10:{s:8:\"aperture\";i:0;s:6:\"credit\";s:0:\"\";s:6:\"camera\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"caption\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"created_timestamp\";i:0;s:9:\"copyright\";s:0:\"\";s:12:\"focal_length\";i:0;s:3:\"iso\";i:0;s:13:\"shutter_speed\";i:0;s:5:\"title\";s:0:\"\";}}'),(6312,732,'_thumbnail_id','733'),(6313,732,'extra_image_1',''),(6314,732,'_extra_image_1','field_52f273e29b5db'),(6315,732,'extra_image_2',''),(6316,732,'_extra_image_2','field_52f27616cf901'),(6317,732,'extra_image_3',''),(6318,732,'_extra_image_3','field_52f27626cf902'),(6319,732,'position','player'),(6320,732,'_position','field_5383fd410a0b4'),(6321,732,'sidebar','school-set-five'),(6322,732,'_sidebar','field_5380e7f58e3e8'),(6323,732,'right_column','<h1>Q &amp; A</h1>\r\n<p><strong>What was your first BATS show?<br /></strong>This may not have been the first but one of the first shows I saw at BATS. I remember coming in late and Regina and Diane were sitting around a campfire, then that ended and some other story came up. I was confused as these different stories came and went, then Regina and Diane were there again around the same fire and it was like a punch in the stomach as I realized they were all jumping form story to story and back again, I\'ll never forget it!</p>\r\n<p><strong>Your first improv class?<br /></strong>My first class at BATS was with Rebecca Stockley. I took Beginning Improv even though I\'d been improvising for several years. I just started at the beginning, and I was so glad I did. It was so much fun and so enlightening.</p>\r\n<p><strong>What are your favorite formats?<br /></strong>I really love them all. For shortform I enjoy playing Free Style. I love watching and performing in Spontaneous Broadway.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Best moment on the BATS stage?<br /></strong>For me recently in the Improvised Downton Abbey, my character was the housekeeper bantering with my staff in the kitchen. There was a moment when I was more character than actor, the staff was being too casual and my character needed to put them in their place, and she did, and the entire audience reacted as one in responding to the quips. There was deep joy in having and sharing that with the audience and my fellow players on stage.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Any improv advice?<br /></strong>Believe it -- literally -- when the great improvisers say \"mistakes are gifts.\" For years I thought on some level that they were \'just being nice\' to us students until we got good and stopped making mistakes. They were not, they were speaking the absolute, literal truth for all improvisers, all the time.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Favorite music?<br /></strong>I love a wide variety of music and will listen to and enjoy all music if it comes from the heart.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Favorite theatre?<br /></strong>I\'m going to take this to mean the actual physical place, in which case it is the New Amsterdam Theatre in New York City. It went from a ruined gem to a wonderfully restored venue thanks to Disney. They restored it for <em>The Lion King,</em> which is spectacular to see in any theater.</p>'),(6324,732,'_right_column','field_52f276e1f1ba0'),(6325,732,'_wp_old_slug','732'),(6326,734,'_edit_lock','1406924781:5'),(6327,734,'_edit_last','4'),(6328,735,'_wp_attached_file','2014/05/LisaSafran_236x236.jpg'),(6329,735,'_wp_attachment_metadata','a:5:{s:5:\"width\";i:237;s:6:\"height\";i:237;s:4:\"file\";s:30:\"2014/05/LisaSafran_236x236.jpg\";s:5:\"sizes\";a:1:{s:9:\"thumbnail\";a:4:{s:4:\"file\";s:30:\"LisaSafran_236x236-150x150.jpg\";s:5:\"width\";i:150;s:6:\"height\";i:150;s:9:\"mime-type\";s:10:\"image/jpeg\";}}s:10:\"image_meta\";a:10:{s:8:\"aperture\";i:0;s:6:\"credit\";s:0:\"\";s:6:\"camera\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"caption\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"created_timestamp\";i:0;s:9:\"copyright\";s:0:\"\";s:12:\"focal_length\";i:0;s:3:\"iso\";i:0;s:13:\"shutter_speed\";i:0;s:5:\"title\";s:0:\"\";}}'),(6330,734,'_thumbnail_id','735'),(6331,734,'extra_image_1',''),(6332,734,'_extra_image_1','field_52f273e29b5db'),(6333,734,'extra_image_2',''),(6334,734,'_extra_image_2','field_52f27616cf901'),(6335,734,'extra_image_3',''),(6336,734,'_extra_image_3','field_52f27626cf902'),(6337,734,'position','player'),(6338,734,'_position','field_5383fd410a0b4'),(6339,734,'sidebar','school-set-five'),(6340,734,'_sidebar','field_5380e7f58e3e8'),(6341,734,'right_column','<h1>Q &amp; A</h1><p><strong>What do you like about improv?<br /></strong>I love that I get to keep learning and finding ways to incorporate it into my life and work. I love the emphasis on making your partner look good -- the getting out of self and seeing what we can do for others is brilliant and something I continue to work on.</p><p><strong>What was your first BATS Show?<br /></strong>I honestly don\'t remember, but I think it was quite a while ago and before the theatre had its makeover. Seeing my first longform was in 2007, and I was blown away.</p><p><strong>Your first improv class?<br /></strong>1985</p><p><strong>What are your favorite formats?<br /></strong>Longform and longform! Having a theatrical background, I am drawn to the stageplay-like qualities and am mesmerized by how all the details tend to fall into place!</p><p><strong>Favorite moment on the BATS stage?<br /></strong>One of my favorite performing moments was during Cave Match when I was in a chase scene with my partner in crime and two \"bad\" guys chasing us. First there was a car chase with shooting out the window and while climbing on the roof, then there was a shootout behind a big boulder, next we were on a plane where I found a gun hidden in the restroom up in the ceiling but the \"bad\" guy ended up being victorious by killing me with a toilet plunger.</p><p><strong>Why should people study improv?<br /></strong>Why not study improv? Improvisation teaches flexibility and agility. It strengthens communication and capacity for leadership. I apply improvisation daily and fail daily at applying it. What I love about improvisation is that each failure is an opportunity and when looked at through that lens, it isn\'t a failure at all. My entire work life is all about improvisation -- from coaching at BATS to working with individuals on presentation skills to designing and delivering corporate and school trainings.</p><p><strong>Any improv advice?<br /></strong>Try it at least once if not a thousand times.</p>'),(6342,734,'_right_column','field_52f276e1f1ba0'),(6343,736,'_edit_lock','1401649001:9'),(6344,736,'_edit_last','2'),(6345,737,'_wp_attached_file','2014/05/david-norfleet_236x236.jpg'),(6346,737,'_wp_attachment_metadata','a:5:{s:5:\"width\";i:235;s:6:\"height\";i:235;s:4:\"file\";s:34:\"2014/05/david-norfleet_236x236.jpg\";s:5:\"sizes\";a:1:{s:9:\"thumbnail\";a:4:{s:4:\"file\";s:34:\"david-norfleet_236x236-150x150.jpg\";s:5:\"width\";i:150;s:6:\"height\";i:150;s:9:\"mime-type\";s:10:\"image/jpeg\";}}s:10:\"image_meta\";a:10:{s:8:\"aperture\";i:0;s:6:\"credit\";s:0:\"\";s:6:\"camera\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"caption\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"created_timestamp\";i:0;s:9:\"copyright\";s:0:\"\";s:12:\"focal_length\";i:0;s:3:\"iso\";i:0;s:13:\"shutter_speed\";i:0;s:5:\"title\";s:0:\"\";}}'),(6347,736,'_thumbnail_id','737'),(6348,736,'extra_image_1',''),(6349,736,'_extra_image_1','field_52f273e29b5db'),(6350,736,'extra_image_2',''),(6351,736,'_extra_image_2','field_52f27616cf901'),(6352,736,'extra_image_3',''),(6353,736,'_extra_image_3','field_52f27626cf902'),(6354,736,'position','player'),(6355,736,'_position','field_5383fd410a0b4'),(6356,736,'sidebar','school-set-five'),(6357,736,'_sidebar','field_5380e7f58e3e8'),(6358,736,'right_column','<h1>Q &amp; A</h1><p><strong>What do you like about improv?<br /></strong>I like the freedom, anything can happen. You can also always be stretching yourself to do new things.</p><p><strong>What was your first BATS Show?<br /></strong>Sunday Players in 1999.</p><p><strong>Your first improv class?  <br /></strong>I\'ve never taken a class. When I started, keyboardists just started playing shows.</p><p><strong>What are your favorite formats?<br /></strong>I like anything longform, especially one that goes the whole evening (both halves).</p><p><strong>Favorite moment on the BATS stage?<br /></strong>There are too many for me to pick.</p><p><strong>Why should people study improv?<br /></strong>Listening. Great improv, like great jazz, happens when the players are listening to each other. Improv teaches this all too rare skill.</p><p><strong>Any improv advice?<br /></strong>Commit. Improv audiences pay to see commitment.</p><p><strong>What are your artistic influences?<br /></strong>Absurdist and Da Da stuff. Love it. Also love a John Waters film.</p><p><strong>Favorite movies?<br /></strong>Anything directed by Stanley Kubrick</p><p><strong>Favorite music?<br /></strong>Beethoven and Rush</p><p><strong>Favorite play?<br /></strong><em>Wozzeck, </em>both as a play and an opera (although <em>Oedipus Rex</em> rocks)</p>'),(6359,736,'_right_column','field_52f276e1f1ba0'),(6364,559,'sidebar','school-set-two'),(6365,559,'_sidebar','field_5380e7f58e3e8'),(6368,408,'faq_4_question','Do I have to take Foundation 1 if I\'m already an experienced improviser? '),(6369,408,'_faq_4_question','field_53739e65e08eb'),(6370,408,'faq_4_answer','<p>Yes. We recommend that everyone start with <a title=\"Foundation 1\" href=\"http://bats.wpengine.com/school/foundation-1/\">Foundation 1</a>, regardless of previous experience. Why? Because we want every student to speak the language of <a title=\"About Improvised Theatre\" href=\"http://bats.wpengine.com/shows/about-improvised-theatre/\">BATS-style improv</a> and be well-versed in its approach.</p><p>For students who have significant equivalent experience, we will sometimes make an exception to this policy. If you believe you fit this description, please contact the office at <strong>(415) 474-6776</strong> or email <a href=\"mailto:registrar@improv.org\">registrar@improv.org</a> to talk to the Dean or Manager of Improv Training Programs.</p>'),(6371,408,'_faq_4_answer','field_53739e8ce08ec'),(6372,408,'faq_5_question','How big are the classes? How much individual attention will I get? How much stage time?'),(6373,408,'_faq_5_question','field_53739e65e08eb'),(6374,408,'faq_5_answer','<p class=\"Body1\">The maximum number of students varies depending on the class. The maximum class size of each class is listed in the class description.</p><p class=\"Body1\">In general, our Foundation level classes are 12-16 students and 1 coach. The more advanced classes are about 10 students and 1 coach. Our coaches are experienced professionals who provide encouragement and constructive, concrete feedback to each student. Stage time is always shared evenly among all members of the class.</p>'),(6375,408,'_faq_5_answer','field_53739e8ce08ec'),(6376,408,'faq_6_question','Can I sit in and watch (audit) a class? '),(6377,408,'_faq_6_question','field_53739e65e08eb'),(6378,408,'faq_6_answer','<p>Sorry, we do not allow students to audit. BATS classes create a safe, supportive environment in which students can take risks and do their best work. Visitors change the class dynamic from \"workshop\" to \"performance.\"</p>'),(6379,408,'_faq_6_answer','field_53739e8ce08ec'),(6380,408,'faq_7_question','Who\'s the best coach?'),(6381,408,'_faq_7_question','field_53739e65e08eb'),(6382,408,'faq_7_answer','<p>All of them! Our coaches wouldn’t be teaching with us if we didn\'t think they were great! <a title=\"BATS Coaches\" href=\"http://bats.wpengine.com/school/bats-coaches/\">BATS Coaches</a> has more info about our talented teaching staff. For an individual bio, click the name or picture of the coach you’re interested in.</p>'),(6383,408,'_faq_7_answer','field_53739e8ce08ec'),(6384,408,'faq_8_question','How do I contact one of the BATS coaches?'),(6385,408,'_faq_8_question','field_53739e65e08eb'),(6386,408,'faq_8_answer','<p>Email <a href=\"http://registrar@improv.org\">registrar@improv.org</a>, and we’ll be happy to forward your question or comment.</p>'),(6387,408,'_faq_8_answer','field_53739e8ce08ec'),(6388,408,'faq2_title','<h2>Registration, Payment, Cancellation, Waitlist, Refunds, Financial Aid</h2>'),(6389,408,'_faq2_title','field_5383f4f709dbb'),(6390,408,'faq2_0_question','How do I enroll?'),(6391,408,'_faq2_0_question','field_53739e65e08eb'),(6392,408,'faq2_0_answer','<p>Registering online is the best way. On each class page’s upcoming class schedule are SIGN UP buttons for each session. Clicking it takes you to the Eventbrite page for that session where you will be able to register (you can pay by credit card or PayPal) and learn more about the class curriculum, goals, and logistics.</p><p>If you cannot register online, call the office at <strong>(415) 474-6776</strong> or email <a href=\"mailto:registrar@improv.org\">registrar@improv.org</a> for assistance. We can make arrangements for payment by check or cash as needed.</p>'),(6393,408,'_faq2_0_answer','field_53739e8ce08ec'),(6394,408,'faq2_1_question','Can I reserve or hold a space in a class? '),(6395,408,'_faq2_1_question','field_53739e65e08eb'),(6396,408,'faq2_1_answer','<p>Due to high demand, the only way to reserve a space is with full payment.</p>'),(6397,408,'_faq2_1_answer','field_53739e8ce08ec'),(6398,408,'faq2_2_question','What forms of payment do you accept?'),(6399,408,'_faq2_2_question','field_53739e65e08eb'),(6400,408,'faq2_2_answer','<p class=\"Body1\">All online class registrations are processed through Eventbrite where you can pay with a credit card or PayPal. This is the best way to lock in your registration and gaurantee a space in the class you want.</p>'),(6401,408,'_faq2_2_answer','field_53739e8ce08ec'),(6402,408,'faq2_3_question','The class I want is sold out. Can I get on a waiting list?'),(6403,408,'_faq2_3_question','field_53739e65e08eb'),(6404,408,'faq2_3_answer','<p>Yes! We offer waiting lists for sold-out classes. If a class is sold out, the Eventbrite registration page will show a waitlist option. (Click WAITLIST and enter your contact information.</p>'),(6405,408,'_faq2_3_answer','field_53739e8ce08ec'),(6406,408,'faq2_4_question','What if BATS cancels my class?'),(6407,408,'_faq2_4_question','field_53739e65e08eb'),(6408,408,'faq2_4_answer','<p class=\"Body1\">If BATS cancels a class that you have paid for, you will receive a refund check for the full tuition. At your discretion, you can also apply any tuition paid as credit toward a future class.</p>'),(6409,408,'_faq2_4_answer','field_53739e8ce08ec'),(6410,408,'faq2_5_question','What if I decide to drop a class? What is the refund policy? '),(6411,408,'_faq2_5_question','field_53739e65e08eb'),(6412,408,'faq2_5_answer','<p>The cost of every class includes a 20% nonrefundable deposit. Our policy for 80% refunds depend on the type of class, as explained below. Refunds are paid by check.</p><p><em>If you drop any class 14 days or more before the first class session<br /></em>You may choose to receive an 80% refund (the amount of the class minus your nonrefundable deposit) OR you may choose to reapply your payment in full to another BATS class.</p><p><em>If you drop a Summer Session or youth/teen class 13 days or fewer before first class session<br /></em>Your payment cannot be reapplied or refunded at all.</p><p><em>If you drop a regular adult class between 13 and 4 days before first class session<br /></em>You lose the option of reapplying your payment in full. You can either reapply your payment minus the deposit to another class OR receive an 80% refund.</p><p><em>If you drop a regular adult class within 72 hours (3 days) of the first class session or after it has begun<br /></em>Your payment cannot be reapplied or refunded at all.</p><p>Here’s why: Although we want to be flexible with changing schedules, it is unlikely we’d be able to fill an extra spot in class at the last minute, so these rules are to ensure the success of the classes. For the same reasons, if you decide you don’t like the class halfway through, we cannot offer any partial refund or reapplication of payment.</p>'),(6413,408,'_faq2_5_answer','field_53739e8ce08ec'),(6414,408,'faq2_6_question','I have to miss the first class of a series I want to take, is that okay? '),(6415,408,'_faq2_6_question','field_53739e65e08eb'),(6416,408,'faq2_6_answer','<p>Generally speaking, we don’t recommend missing the first class of any series. The first class is very important in establishing the class dynamic, and we highly recommend that you find a series where you can attend the first (and all) of the sessions. If you still want to register for a class where you will miss the first meeting, please contact the office in advance at <strong>(415) 474-6776</strong> or <a href=\"mailto:registrar@improv.org\">registrar@improv.org</a><strong>.</strong></p>'),(6417,408,'_faq2_6_answer','field_53739e8ce08ec'),(6418,408,'faq2_7_question','What if I miss a class? '),(6419,408,'_faq2_7_question','field_53739e65e08eb'),(6420,408,'faq2_7_answer','<p class=\"Body1\">If you miss a class, you will miss a class. BATS cannot refund your payment or prorate your class tuition in advance to account for the missed class.</p>'),(6421,408,'_faq2_7_answer','field_53739e8ce08ec'),(6422,408,'faq2_8_question','If I miss a class, can I make it up somehow? '),(6423,408,'_faq2_8_question','field_53739e65e08eb'),(6424,408,'faq2_8_answer','<p class=\"Body1\">We don\'t offer makeup classes at BATS. We highly recommend that you register for a series where you can attend all the class meetings. Here’s why: Each class develops its own dynamic and that dynamic is key to everyone’s success. Having a new student drop in in for just one class disrupts the dynamic and interferes with the creative process.</p>'),(6425,408,'_faq2_8_answer','field_53739e8ce08ec'),(6426,408,'faq2_9_question','What\'s the penalty for a bounced check? '),(6427,408,'_faq2_9_question','field_53739e65e08eb'),(6428,408,'faq2_9_answer','<p class=\"Body1\">You will be charged a $25 fee for any bounced checks.</p>'),(6429,408,'_faq2_9_answer','field_53739e8ce08ec'),(6430,408,'faq2_10_question','Do you offer financial aid or scholarships? '),(6431,408,'_faq2_10_question','field_53739e65e08eb'),(6432,408,'faq2_10_answer','<p>BATS Improv offers a limited number of need-based scholarships on a recurring basis. Applicants must submit a copy of their most recent tax return along with a one-page letter explaining how this course will make a constructive difference in their lives. Letters on behalf of student-age applicants may be written by parents or guardians. Scholarship aid covers 50% - 100% of the total cost of the course. Each qualified student is allowed a maximum of two scholarships per 12-month period. Materials should be emailed to <a href=\"http://registrar@improv.org\">registrar@improv.org</a>.</p><p>BATS also offers a <strong>Work Study Program</strong> that allows students to earn up to 75% of the tuition for BATS classes by working at Friday or Saturday shows. Inquire in the office to get more details and learn how you can apply.</p>'),(6433,408,'_faq2_10_answer','field_53739e8ce08ec'),(6434,408,'faq2','11'),(6435,408,'_faq2','field_5383f210359a2'),(6436,748,'_wp_attached_file','2014/04/map_batsTheater.jpg'),(6437,748,'_wp_attachment_metadata','a:5:{s:5:\"width\";i:685;s:6:\"height\";i:210;s:4:\"file\";s:27:\"2014/04/map_batsTheater.jpg\";s:5:\"sizes\";a:2:{s:9:\"thumbnail\";a:4:{s:4:\"file\";s:27:\"map_batsTheater-150x150.jpg\";s:5:\"width\";i:150;s:6:\"height\";i:150;s:9:\"mime-type\";s:10:\"image/jpeg\";}s:6:\"medium\";a:4:{s:4:\"file\";s:26:\"map_batsTheater-300x91.jpg\";s:5:\"width\";i:300;s:6:\"height\";i:91;s:9:\"mime-type\";s:10:\"image/jpeg\";}}s:10:\"image_meta\";a:10:{s:8:\"aperture\";i:0;s:6:\"credit\";s:0:\"\";s:6:\"camera\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"caption\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"created_timestamp\";i:0;s:9:\"copyright\";s:0:\"\";s:12:\"focal_length\";i:0;s:3:\"iso\";i:0;s:13:\"shutter_speed\";i:0;s:5:\"title\";s:0:\"\";}}'),(6438,749,'_wp_attached_file','2014/04/map_studio210.jpg'),(6439,749,'_wp_attachment_metadata','a:5:{s:5:\"width\";i:332;s:6:\"height\";i:332;s:4:\"file\";s:25:\"2014/04/map_studio210.jpg\";s:5:\"sizes\";a:2:{s:9:\"thumbnail\";a:4:{s:4:\"file\";s:25:\"map_studio210-150x150.jpg\";s:5:\"width\";i:150;s:6:\"height\";i:150;s:9:\"mime-type\";s:10:\"image/jpeg\";}s:6:\"medium\";a:4:{s:4:\"file\";s:25:\"map_studio210-300x300.jpg\";s:5:\"width\";i:300;s:6:\"height\";i:300;s:9:\"mime-type\";s:10:\"image/jpeg\";}}s:10:\"image_meta\";a:10:{s:8:\"aperture\";i:0;s:6:\"credit\";s:0:\"\";s:6:\"camera\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"caption\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"created_timestamp\";i:0;s:9:\"copyright\";s:0:\"\";s:12:\"focal_length\";i:0;s:3:\"iso\";i:0;s:13:\"shutter_speed\";i:0;s:5:\"ti