jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(295,2,'2014-04-09 10:45:17','2014-04-09 17:45:17','','about6','','inherit','open','open','','about6','','','2014-04-09 10:45:17','2014-04-09 17:45:17','',14,'http://bats.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/about6.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(296,2,'2014-04-09 10:53:45','2014-04-09 17:53:45','<h1><img class=\"alignright size-full wp-image-822\" src=\"http://bats.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/about_ourvision_candid-on-stage.jpg\" alt=\"about_ourvision_candid-on-stage\" width=\"332\" height=\"207\" />Our Vision</h1><p class=\"Body1\">We envision a world where everyone is comfortable in their own skin, where ideas and flights of fancy are encouraged, respected, and given wondrous, unimaginable form through spirited, skillful collaboration.</p><p class=\"Body1\">Where life itself is recognized as improvisational and the skills of improvised theatre are embraced as life skills.</p><p class=\"Body1\">Where the art of improvised theatre is broadly enjoyed and the BATS style of storytelling is acknowledged as an essential way to celebrate our shared experience.</p><p class=\"Body1\">Where BATS Improv-trained performers are recognized for their unique ability to capture the depth and humor of the human condition.</p><p class=\"Body1\">Where, accessible to all, BATS Improv continues to explore and innovate, fading the line between actor and audience to create a community of kindred spirits and a one-of-a-kind theatrical experience.</p><p class=\"Body1\">In this future, our world is a brighter, more accepting, more creative place where everyone wants to live, if only one show or class at a time.</p>','Our Vision','','publish','open','open','','our-vision','','','2014-05-30 16:11:41','2014-05-30 23:11:41','',14,'http://bats.wpengine.com/?page_id=296',25,'page','',0),(298,2,'2014-04-09 10:55:08','2014-04-09 17:55:08','<h1><img class=\"alignright size-full wp-image-723\" src=\"http://bats.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/staff-photo.jpg\" alt=\"staff-photo\" width=\"332\" height=\"222\" />Staff &amp; Board</h1>\r\n<h3>Staff</h3>\r\n<p><strong>Artistic Director:</strong> <a title=\"Kasey Klemm\" href=\"http://bats.wpengine.com/actors/kasey-klemm/\">Kasey Klemm</a></p>\r\n<p><strong>Managing Director:</strong> <a title=\"Chet Anderson\" href=\"http://bats.wpengine.com/about-us/chet-anderson/\">Chet Anderson</a></p>\r\n<p><strong>Dean, BATS School of Improv:</strong> <a title=\"Regina Saisi\" href=\"http://bats.wpengine.com/actors/regini-saisi/\">Regina Saisi</a></p>\r\n<p><strong>Director, BATS On-the-Go:</strong> Ceci Walken</p>\r\n<p><strong>Manager of Training Programs:</strong> <a title=\"Rebecca Poretsky\" href=\"http://bats.wpengine.com/actors/rebecca-poretsky/\">Rebecca Poretsky</a></p>\r\n<p><strong>Summer Sessions Coordinator and Youth Director:</strong> <a title=\"Laura Derry\" href=\"http://bats.wpengine.com/actors/laura-derry/\">Laura Derry</a></p>\r\n<p><strong>Program Assistant:</strong> Mona Thompson</p>\r\n<p><strong>Laughing Stock Coordinator:</strong> Ann Feehan</p>\r\n<p><strong>House Managers:</strong> Jesse DeGuzman, Larissa Kasian</p>\r\n<p><strong>Musical Director:</strong> <a title=\"Joshua Raoul Brody, Musical Director\" href=\"http://bats.wpengine.com/actors/joshua-raoul-brody-musical-director/\">Joshua Raoul Brody</a></p>\r\n<p><strong>Musical Improvisers:</strong> <a title=\"Joshua Raoul Brody, Musical Director\" href=\"http://bats.wpengine.com/actors/joshua-raoul-brody-musical-director/\">Joshua Raoul Brody</a>, <a title=\"David Norfleet\" href=\"http://bats.wpengine.com/actors/david-norfleet/\">David Norfleet</a>, Richard Leiter, Steve Kirk, Win Meyerson, Joey Hassid, Jerome Rossen</p>\r\n<p><strong>Lighting Improvisers:</strong> Alva Ackley, Craig Good, Rez Graham</p>\r\n<hr />\r\n<h3>Board of Directors</h3>\r\n<p><strong>Joshua Heller</strong>, President<br /><em>Senior Account Executive,</em> Oracle Responsys</p>\r\n<p><strong>David Boyll</strong>, Vice President<br /> <em>Director, Digital Media Technology,</em> Oracle</p>\r\n<p><strong>Ed Alter</strong>, Treasurer<br /> <em>Partner &amp; Director of Business Development,</em> SpeechSkills, LLC</p>\r\n<p><strong>Jerry Ruoti</strong>, Secretary<br /> <em>Product Support Project Manager,</em> Facebook</p>\r\n<p><strong>Michael Anderson</strong><br /> <em>Senior Manager, Strategy &amp; Enablement,</em> Salesforce.com</p>\r\n<p><strong>Gemma Bulos</strong><br /> <em>Founder,</em> Single Drop</p>\r\n<p><strong>Thomas Butler</strong><br /> <em>Vice President, Wealth Management Group,</em> Bank of the West</p>\r\n<p><strong>Paul Killam</strong><br /> <em>Company Member and Artistic Director Emeritus,</em> BATS Improv</p>\r\n<p><strong>Lisa Rowland</strong><br /> <em>Company Member and former Manager of Training Programs,</em> BATS Improv</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<hr />\r\n<p><strong>Website Photography</strong><br /> Jenn Dorn, William Hall, Dan Heller, Petr Jerabek, Ben Long, Stephanie Pool, Corey Rosen</p>\r\n<hr />','Staff & Board','','publish','open','open','','staff-board','','','2015-03-10 16:11:22','2015-03-10 23:11:22','',14,'http://bats.wpengine.com/?page_id=298',24,'page','',0),(299,2,'2014-04-09 10:55:37','2014-04-09 17:55:37','<h1><img class=\"alignright size-full wp-image-477\" src=\"http://bats.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/community.jpg\" alt=\"community\" width=\"332\" height=\"193\" />Community Outreach Programs</h1><p>The first thing to learn about improv is that you’re not in it alone. As a nonprofit San Francisco institution, we feel strongly about giving back to the Bay Area community that sustains us as we build an improvised theatre community from the grassroots.</p><p>BATS is not just a theatre company, and it’s not just a school. It’s a center for improvised theatre -- a community of people who share our vision, who want to challenge themselves, to have fun, to connect with others who feel the same way. In this integrated improvisational universe, it’s imperative that we bring the skills and delight of improvised theatre to the broadest possible group of people. That means keeping our classes and shows affordable in order to ensure that they are accessible to everyone. To accomplish this goal, we’ve created the following programs.</p><hr /><h3><img class=\"alignleft size-full wp-image-479\" src=\"http://bats.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/laughing.jpg\" alt=\"laughing\" width=\"215\" height=\"143\" />Laughing Stock</h3><p>For the past 15 years, we have provided free improv classes to people living with chronic and life-threatening illnesses through our Laughing Stock program. These sessions, available to caregivers as well as those living with illness, focus on improving quality of life through humor, easy physical activity, group interaction, gentle risk-taking, and imagination games. Our experienced coaches create a safe and confidential environment for participants to learn the basics of Improv.</p><p>A Laughing Stock session is not stand-up comedy or drama therapy but a fun workshop for folks with any level of experience with improv (including none). Most sessions cover the basics of improv, but the program occasionally includes specialty workshops such as improvised writing, singing, masks, and movement.</p><p>Please call the office at <strong>(415) 474-6776</strong> or email <a href=\"mailto:laughingstock@improv.org\">laughingstock@improv.org</a> to learn more.</p><div class=\"blue-quote\"><h4 style=\"text-align: left;\">“I gained increased self-confidence.”</h4><p style=\"text-align: right;\"><em>- Laughing Stock participant</em></p></div><hr /><h3>Scholarships for Classes &amp; Work Study Program</h3><p>The BATS School of Improv offers need-based scholarships for youth and adult classes. Please call the office at <strong>(415) 474-6776</strong> or email <a href=\"mailto:registrar@improv.org\">registrar@improv.org</a> to learn more.</p><p>BATS also offers a Work Study Program that allows students to earn up to 75% of the tuition for BATS classes by working at Friday or Saturday shows. Please call the office at <strong>(415) 474-6776</strong> or email <a href=\"mailto:registrar@improv.org\">registrar@improv.org</a> to learn more.</p><div class=\"blue-quote\"><h4 style=\"text-align: left;\">“I am really impressed and touched by their scholarship program. I’ve been evangelizing to friends ever since.”</h4><p style=\"text-align: right;\"><em>- BATS student (from anonymous survey)</em></p></div><hr /><h3><img class=\"alignright size-full wp-image-480\" src=\"http://bats.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/festivals.jpg\" alt=\"festivals\" width=\"215\" height=\"152\" />Free Festivals</h3><p>BATS Improv participates in a number of free festivals and special events including <a href=\"http://www.sftheaterfestival.org\" target=\"_blank\">San Francisco TheaterFest</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.tcg.org/events/freenight\" target=\"_blank\">Free Night of Theater</a> program.</p><div class=\"blue-quote\"><h4 style=\"text-align: left;\">“We love taking our playful theatre out into the community and engaging with new audiences.”</h4><p style=\"text-align: right;\"><em>- Kasey Klemm, Artistic Director</em> </p></div><hr /><h3>Charity Entertainment &amp; Donations</h3><p>At least once per year, members of the BATS Main Stage Company perform at charity fundraisers and for special groups who are unable to come to a show. We also donate tickets frequently as raffle prizes or auction items for schools, nonprofits, and other charity organizations and offer free tickets to economically challenged schools. Please call the office at <strong>(415) 474-6776</strong> or email <a href=\"mailto:shows@improv.org\">shows@improv.org</a> to learn more.</p><div class=\"blue-quote\"><h4 style=\"text-align: left;\">“I wanted to thank you again for the tremendous talent you pulled together for our event. It was such a pleasure to present BATS . . . Really impressive, exceptional talent.”</h4><p style=\"text-align: right;\"><em>- Kimberly Gordon, Peninsula Jewish Community Center</em></p></div><hr />','Community Outreach','','publish','open','open','','community-outreach','','','2014-05-30 09:18:40','2014-05-30 16:18:40','',14,'http://bats.wpengine.com/?page_id=299',23,'page','',0),(300,2,'2014-04-09 10:55:58','2014-04-09 17:55:58','<h1>History of BATS Improv</h1><p>BATS Improv traces its philosophical roots back to the work of Keith Johnstone, author of Impro, creator of Theatresports<sup>TM</sup>, and one of the few internationally recognized authorities on improvised theatre.</p><p><img class=\"alignright size-full wp-image-721\" src=\"http://bats.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/history-photo.jpg\" alt=\"history-photo\" width=\"215\" height=\"236\" />During his tenure at the London Royal Court Theatre in the 1950s and 60s, Johnstone developed a series of improvisational exercises to help playwrights overcome writer\'s block by short-circuiting the natural tendency to edit themselves. He captured this work in his first book, <a href=\"http://www.eventbrite.com/e/book-impro-improvisation-and-the-theatre-by-keith-johnstone-tickets-376190195&gt;\" target=\"_blank\"><em>Impro: Improvisation and the Theatre</em></a>. Johnstone also went on to develop the Theatresports format, in which two teams of improvisers “compete” and the audience becomes vested spectators in a battle to create the best theatre possible.</p><p>As performers from around the world discovered Theatresports, they formed their own companies dedicated to the improvisational format. One such company was Seattle Theatresports (now Unexpected Productions), founded in 1983 and the first U.S. company to perform the format. <strong>And this is where the real story of BATS begins!</strong></p>\r\n<hr />\r\n<h2>BATS Improv: A Timeline</h2><p><strong>November 1986:</strong> A San Francisco comedy theatre group, Fratelli Bologna, invites <a title=\"Rebecca Stockley\" href=\"http://bats.wpengine.com/actors/rebecca-stockley/\">Rebecca Stockley</a>, a teacher from Seattle Theatresports, to lead a workshop and teach the Theatresports format.</p><p><strong>November 10, 1986:</strong> Stockley\'s workshop culminates in a sold-out performance at the Zephyr Theater (now New Conservatory Theatre). Several actors in the audience that night will later join the founding members to form a new company of improvisers in San Francisco: <strong>Bay Area Theatresports</strong>. (<a title=\"BATS Alumni\" href=\"http://bats.wpengine.com/about-us/history/alumni/\">See the list of past BATS Main Stage Company members</a>.)</p><p><strong>1987:</strong> Bay Area Theatresports forms its first performing company and begins offering classes. The Company performs in spaces throughout San Francisco: the New Performance Gallery, the New Conservatory Theatre, the Asian American Theater, 450 Geary, and the Bayfront Theater, among others.</p><p><strong>1988:</strong> BATS begins renting space at Army Street Studios, which is its home for several years. BATS alumni found Los Angeles Theatresports (now Impro Theatre).</p><p><strong>1988-1989:</strong> Driven by a love of theatre and fully developed stories and characters, BATS begins performing <strong>longform</strong> improvisation shows. This new form of improv was being explored by the SF company Improv Theater, with whom BATS shared several cast members. The form took hold quickly at BATS, and the company continues to pioneer single-story longform improvisation to this day.</p><p><strong>1991:</strong> BATS hosts <strong>International Theatresports Tournaments</strong> at the Magic Theater, drawing improvisers from around the globe.</p><p><strong>1991:</strong> The <strong>BATS School of Improv</strong> is founded as BATS begins offering regular workshops to the general public. Students from BATS workshops begin performing at the Phoenix Theater as “The Workshop Players.”</p><p><strong>1994:</strong> BATS offers its first summer school session in conjunction with Stanford University, featuring a residency with Keith Johnstone. The BATS <a title=\"Summer Sessions\" href=\"http://bats.wpengine.com/school/summer-sessions/\">Summer Sessions</a> program became an annual tradition, and today it draws students from as far away as Australia, Europe, and Japan.</p><p><strong>1994:</strong> BATS holds its first annual <strong>Summer Improv Festival</strong> in August.</p><p><strong>1996:</strong> As the number of BATS student performers grows, the <strong>Sunday Players</strong> performing ensemble replaces the Workshop Players. The Sunday Players go on to perform Sunday nights at BATS until 2010.</p><p><strong>1997:</strong> BATS takes up permanent residency at the <strong>Bayfront Theater</strong> in the historic Fort Mason Center and experiences tremendous growth. The company adds more classes and workshops and expands its performance schedule to three shows a week.</p><p><strong>1998:</strong> BATS begins its <a title=\"Community Outreach\" href=\"http://bats.wpengine.com/about-us/community-outreach/\">Laughing Stock</a> program, offering free improv classes to people living with chronic, life-threatening illnesses and to their partners and caregivers.</p><p><strong>1998:</strong> BATS is voted \"Best Improv Company\" for the first time in the <em>SF Bay Guardian</em>\'s annual Best of the Bay poll. Since then, BATS has been recognized with 17 more <strong>“Best of” awards</strong> from the <em>Guardian,</em> the <em>SF Weekly, 7x7, San Francisco</em>, and the <em>San Francisco Chronicle</em> as well as being Highly Recommended 2010 to the present by <em>Frommer’s Travel Guide</em>.</p><p><strong>1999:</strong> <strong>The Belfry</strong>, a Thursday night performing group is formed. The Belfry performed until 2002.</p><p><strong>2000: </strong>BATS formally creates a corporate training and entertainment division (now known as <strong>BATS On-the-Go</strong>).</p><p><strong>2001: </strong>Bay Area Theatresports formally becomes “<strong>BATS Improv</strong>.”</p><p><strong>2002:</strong> BATS creates one of the nation’s finest performance settings devoted exclusively to improv theatre through a series of fundraising campaigns and capital improvement projects. A completely <strong>renovated Bayfront Theater</strong> opens, including new lobby and concession areas and new seats</p><p><strong>2005:</strong> After another sucessful fundraising campaign, BATS builds a brand new wheelchair-accessible stage.</p><p><strong>2006:</strong> BATS Improv celebrates 20 years and is recoginized by the City of San Francisco as November 10, 2006, is declared <strong>BATS Improv Day</strong>.</p><p><strong>2011:</strong> BATS begins performing Theatresports<sup>TM</sup> and other shortform shows every Friday and genre-driven longform shows every Saturday.</p><p><strong>Summer 2014:</strong> BATS holds it’s 20<sup>th</sup> Annual Summer Improv Festival and Summer Sessions workshops!</p><p><strong>2014:</strong> BATS Improv continues to be the Bay Area\'s premiere improvised theatre company and school, attracting more than 11,000 audience members and 1,300 workshop enrollments every year.</p>','History','','publish','open','open','','history','','','2014-05-31 15:41:04','2014-05-31 22:41:04','',14,'http://bats.wpengine.com/?page_id=300',21,'page','',0),(301,2,'2014-04-09 10:56:27','2014-04-09 17:56:27','<h1>Map, Directions &amp; Nearby</h1><p><a href=\"https://www.google.com/maps/place/BATS+Improv+Theatre/@37.817717,-122.430696,4328m/data=!3m1!1e3!4m2!3m1!1s0x0:0x48b36832e74af2b7?hl=en\" target=\"_blank\"><img class=\"alignleft wp-image-748 size-full\" style=\"margin-bottom: 20px;\" src=\"http://bats.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/map_batsTheater.jpg\" alt=\"map_batsTheater\" width=\"685\" height=\"210\" /></a></p><h2>Bayfront Theater</h2><p>Building B, Third floor<br />Fort Mason Center, San Francisco</p><p><strong>BATS Improv is located in the Bayfront Theater</strong>, on the third floor of Building B at <a href=\"http://www.fortmason.org\" target=\"_blank\">Fort Mason Center (FMC)</a>. FMC is located in the beautiful San Francisco Marina District between Fisherman\'s Wharf and the Golden Gate Bridge. </p><p>(<strong><em>GPS and Google Map users:</em> </strong>FMC does not have a street address other than \"Fort Mason Center.\" You can use \"Marina Blvd at Buchanan St.\" as your destination, which will direct you to the parking lot entrance, or you can use “16 Marina Blvd,” which will take you to the Safeway directly across from the Fort Mason Center entrance.)</p><p>The auto entrance to FMC is at the intersection of Marina Boulevard and Buchanan Street, across from the Marina Safeway. After you enter the first parking area keep right to enter FMC. Building B is the second from the left if you are facing the water. The BATS Improv entrance is on the left side of the building (facing Greens restaurant). Once inside, take the elevator or stairs to the third floor.</p><p><strong><em>Accessibility: </em></strong>The Bayfront Theater and classrooms in Fort Mason are wheelchair accessible. There is a ramp at the south side (nearest the parking lot) of the west entrance to the building (the entrance with the BATS sign) and an elevator to get to the third floor. ADA-compliant bathrooms are located across the bridge in Building C. Please email <a href=\"mailto:bats@improv.org\" target=\"_blank\">BATS@improv.org</a> to notify us of any special needs you may have so we can accommodate them.</p><hr /><h3>Driving Directions</h3><p><strong>From the East Bay</strong></p><ul><li>Bay Bridge to Fremont St. exit; stay on Fremont (100 yards north)</li><li>Right on Howard (first right off of exit)</li><li>Left onto Embarcadero and go ~ 2 miles</li><li>Left onto Bay and go 2 miles</li><li>Right on Buchanan St.</li><li>Cross Marina Blvd. and take a sharp right into the parking lot</li><li>Keep right and proceed to the Fort Mason Center parking lot</li></ul><p><strong>From the North Bay</strong></p><ul><li>Take the Golden Gate Bridge (US 101)</li><li>Head toward San Francisco and exit at Marina Blvd.</li><li>Go 1.5 miles to Buchanan St.</li><li>Left into the parking lot and immediate right toward Fort Mason Center parking</li></ul><p><strong>From the South Bay/Peninsula</strong></p><ul><li>Take US 101 North to the 9th St. Exit</li><li>Take 9th Street across Market St.</li><li>Left onto Hayes St.</li><li>Right onto Franklin St.</li><li>Left onto Bay St.</li><li>Right onto Buchanan St.</li><li>Cross Marina Blvd. to enter lot and immediate right toward Fort Mason Center parking</li></ul><hr /><h3>Parking</h3><p>Enter at the intersection of Buchanan St. and Marina Blvd. Make a sharp right and go past the gate to park in Fort Mason Center (nominal <a href=\"http://www.fortmason.org/aboutus/visitor-information\" target=\"_blank\">parking fees</a> apply) or make a left to park along the Marina Green (this lot is free but has restricted hours – please check signs carefully).</p><hr /><h3>Public Transportation</h3><p>Several bus (MUNI) lines stop close to Fort Mason Center:</p><ul><li>10 Townsend (comes from the Financial District)</li><li>22 Fillmore (comes from Potrero Hill, up along Fillmore, stopping just a few blocks away)</li><li>28 - 19th Avenue (comes from SFSU and stops right outside the FMC gates)</li><li>30 Stockton</li><li>47 Van Ness (comes straight up Van Ness, stopping just a few blocks away)</li><li>49 Van Ness/Mission (comes straight up Van Ness, stopping just a few blocks away)</li><li>82x Presidio/Wharves Express</li></ul><p>Need more help? Try the Bay Area public transportation <a href=\"http://www.511.org\" target=\"_blank\">Trip Planner</a> (511.org).</p><hr /><p><a name=\"restaurants\"></a></p><div><h3>Nearby Food and Drink</h3><p><a href=\"http://goo.gl/maps/LS3vI\" target=\"_blank\"><img class=\"alignleft wp-image-752 size-full\" style=\"margin-right: 20px; margin-bottom: 20px;\" src=\"http://bats.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/map_restaurants.jpg\" alt=\"map_restaurants\" width=\"332\" height=\"332\" /></a>A. <a href=\"http://www.greensrestaurant.com\" target=\"_blank\">Greens</a> (vegetarian)<br />B. <a href=\"http://offthegridsf.com/markets/fort-mason-center\" target=\"_blank\">Off the Grid</a> (Friday night food truck festival)<br />C. <a href=\"http://www.jakessteaks.net\" target=\"_blank\">Jake’s Steaks</a> (sports bar, sandwiches)<br />D. <a href=\"http://www.benjarongthaisf.com\" target=\"_blank\">Benjarong</a> (Thai, vegetarian)<br />E. <a href=\"http://www.silvercloudssf.com\" target=\"_blank\">Silver Clouds</a> (karaoke bar &amp; grill)<br />F. <a href=\"http://www.alegriassf.com\" target=\"_blank\">Alegrias</a> (Spanish)<br />G. <a href=\"http://www.massake.com\" target=\"_blank\">Mas Sake</a> (Japanese-Mexican, DJ)<br />H. <a href=\"http://www.patxispizza.com\" target=\"_blank\">Patxi’s Chicago Pizza</a> (pizza)<br />I. <a href=\"http://www.sweetaromarestaurant.com\" target=\"_blank\">Sweet Aroma</a> (Vietnamese)<br />J. <a href=\"http://pacificcatch.com/menus/marina\" target=\"_blank\">Pacific Catch</a> (seafood)<br />K. <a href=\"http://tacolicious.com\" target=\"_blank\">Tacolicious</a> (Mexican)<br />L. <a href=\"http://www.barneyshamburgers.com\" target=\"_blank\">Barney’s</a> (gourmet hamburgers)</p><p>We do our best to keep this list current, but it’s always a good idea to check. Bon appetit!</p></div><div class=\"clear\"></div><hr /><div><h1>Studio 210</h1><p><a href=\"http://goo.gl/maps/ikQQJ\" target=\"_blank\"><img class=\"alignleft wp-image-749 size-full\" style=\"margin-right: 20px;\" src=\"http://bats.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/map_studio210.jpg\" alt=\"map_studio210\" width=\"332\" height=\"332\" /></a>3435 Cesar Chavez Street<br />San Francisco</p><p>BATS School of Improv holds classes in Studio 210 as well as the Bayfront Theater and the Cubberley Community Center in Palo Alto. </p><p><strong><em>Accessibility:</em> </strong>Unfortunately, Studio 210 is not wheelchair accessible.</p><p><strong><em>Parking:</em> </strong>Free street parking is available around the building, and generally not too hard to find. You may want to leave a couple of extra minutes just to be sure you find a spot.</p><p><strong><em>Public Transportation:</em></strong> Studio 210 is just a few blocks from the 24th/Mission BART station and easily accessed by many city buses (12, 14, 27, 36, 49). </p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><em><strong>Nearby Food</strong></em><br />Taqueria Cancun (3211 Mission St.)<br />Sweet Basil Thai Cuisine (3221 Mission St.)<br />Pi Bar (1432 Valencia St.)<br />Rosamunde Sausage Grill (2832 Mission St.)<br />Papalote Mexican Grill (3409 24th St.) </p></div><div class=\"clear\"></div><hr /><div><h1>Cubberley Community Center</h1><p><a href=\"http://goo.gl/maps/UU71J\" target=\"_blank\"><img class=\"alignleft wp-image-750 size-full\" style=\"margin-right: 20px;\" src=\"http://bats.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/map_paloalto.jpg\" alt=\"map_paloalto\" width=\"332\" height=\"332\" /></a>4000 Middlefield Road<br />Palo Alto</p><p>BATS School of Improv holds classes in the Cubberley Community Center in Palo Alto as well as the Bayfront Theater and Studio 210 in San Francisco.</p><p><strong><em>Accessibility:</em> </strong>The Cubberley Community Center is wheelchair accessible.<strong> </strong></p><p><strong><em>Parking:</em> </strong>Free parking is available in the <a href=\"http://www.cityofpaloalto.org/civicax/filebank/documents/39570\" target=\"_blank\">Cubberley parking lot</a>.</p><p><strong><em>Public Transportation:</em> </strong>Cubberley is one mile from the San Antonio Caltrain Station and accessible by bus (35, 32).</p><p><em><strong>Nearby Food<br /></strong></em>Green Elephant Gourmet (3950 Middlefield Rd.)<br />Rojoz Gourmet Wraps (3906 Middlefield Rd.)<br />Las Muchachas (2483 Old Middlefield Way) </p><hr /><h3>Safety Information</h3><p>We encourage you to help each other out by providing rides to public transportation, walking together to your cars, and carpooling. As with any urban environment, be aware of your surroundings when walking after dark and use common sense. If you ever feel concerned about safety, please check in with your instructor and he/she will make sure you find company walking out.</p></div>','Map & Directions','','publish','open','open','','map-directions','','','2014-05-31 15:48:54','2014-05-31 22:48:54','',14,'http://bats.wpengine.com/?page_id=301',20,'page','',0),(302,2,'2014-04-09 10:57:31','2014-04-09 17:57:31','<h1>Jobs &amp; Auditions</h1><h3>Jobs</h3><p>Click the job title to open a PDF that includes the job description, requirements, and instructions for how to apply. Jobs will remain listed until the position has been filled.</p><p><a title=\"Volunteer\" href=\"http://bats.wpengine.com/support-bats/volunteer/\">Usher (Volunteer)</a><br />Ongoing positions available</p><p><a title=\"Volunteer\" href=\"http://bats.wpengine.com/support-bats/volunteer/\">Volunteering</a> is a great way to have fun, spend time with cool people, and see a free show! </p><hr /><h3>Auditions</h3><p>BATS School of Improv holds auditions for class placement on a case-by-case basis for new students with previous, equivalent improv training. To inquire about a school audition, please email <strong><a href=\"mailto:dean@improv.org\">dean@improv.org</a></strong>.</p><p>The BATS Main Stage Company holds annual auditions in April for its Company Guest Program. The Company Guest Program is an excellent training and performance opportunity for experienced improvisers. Particiapants in the Guest Program perform and train alongside the BATS Main Stage Company for nine months.</p><p>A link with more information will be posted on this page each year when we begin accepting applications. If you have questions about the Guest Program and auditions, please email <a href=\"mailto:bats@improv.org\" target=\"_blank\">bats@improv.org</a>.</p>','Jobs & Auditions','','publish','open','closed','','jobs-auditions','','','2014-05-31 15:50:54','2014-05-31 22:50:54','',14,'http://bats.wpengine.com/?page_id=302',19,'page','',0),(303,2,'2014-04-09 10:58:11','2014-04-09 17:58:11','<h1>BATS News</h1><p>For media requests, please contact <a href=\"http://hamiltoninkpr.com\" target=\"_blank\">Hamilton Ink</a> via <a href=\"mailto:stephanie@hamiltoninkpr.com\">email</a> or phone (415) 381-8198.</p><p>&nbsp;</p>','News & Announcements','','publish','open','open','','news-announcements','','','2014-05-31 18:30:19','2014-06-01 01:30:19','',14,'http://bats.wpengine.com/?page_id=303',18,'page','',0),(304,2,'2014-04-09 10:58:42','2014-04-09 17:58:42','<h1>Contact Us</h1>\r\n<p><strong>BATS Improv </strong><br /><strong>Center for Improvised Theatre<br /></strong>Fort Mason Center<br />2 Marina Blvd, Bldg B<br />San Francisco, California 94123<br /><a title=\"Map &amp; Directions\" href=\"http://bats.wpengine.com/about-us/map-directions/\">Directions</a></p>\r\n<p><strong>Show information:</strong> (415) 474-8935<br /><strong>Staff and office:</strong> (415) 474-6776<br /><strong>Email:</strong> <a href=\"mailto:bats@improv.org\" target=\"_blank\">bats@improv.org</a><br />Click the names below to email that person directly.</p>\r\n<hr />\r\n<h3>Administration</h3>\r\n<p><strong>Artistic Director:</strong> <a href=\"mailto:kasey@improv.org\" target=\"_blank\">Kasey Klemm</a><br /><strong>Managing Director:</strong> <a href=\"mailto:chet@improv.org\" target=\"_blank\">Chet Anderson</a><br /><strong>Program Assistant:</strong> <a href=\"mailto:mona@improv.org\" target=\"_blank\">Mona Thompson</a></p>\r\n<hr />\r\n<h3>BATS School of Improv</h3>\r\n<p><strong>Dean:</strong> <a href=\"mailto:dean@improv.org\" target=\"_blank\">Regina Saisi</a><br /><strong>Manager of Training Programs:</strong> <a href=\"mailto:rebecca@improv.org\" target=\"_blank\">Rebecca Poretsky</a></p>\r\n<hr />\r\n