-06-03 23:54:40','<h1>The End<br />Tuesday, 7:00 - 10:00 PM</h1>\r\n<p><strong>June 17, 2014<br /> Bayfront Theater, San Francisco</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Schedule</strong>: One session<br /> <strong>Class date:</strong> June 17<br /> <strong>Class length</strong>: 3 hours<br /> <strong>Tuition</strong>: $45<br /> <strong>Prerequisite:</strong> Foundation 3 and above </p>\r\n<p><span style=\"color: #222222;\">Hey there, prospective students!  You know that awkward moment when it seems like you should be at the </span><span style=\"color: #222222;\">end</span><span style=\"color: #222222;\"> of a scene, but somehow find yourselves circling the landing over and over, unable to </span><span style=\"color: #222222;\">end?</span><span style=\"color: #222222;\">  The scene goes on and on until a horn is honked, an arm is feverishly waved, or the lights just tentatively fade down.  </span></p>\r\n<p>When we started discussing my teaching of a class, my fellow improvisers and instructors started pointing to my knack for ending scenes with a button that is comical while it gently and logically ended the scene.  By looking at the story arc and your own style of improv, let\'s spread the gift of ending scenes at their conclusion. </p>\r\n<p>And we\'ll talk a little Scooby Doo while we\'re at it. Seriously.  </p>\r\n<p>Interested?</p>','The End with Kimberly MacLean (#06-1949)','','publish','open','open','','the-end-with-kimberly-maclean-06-1949','','','2014-06-03 16:56:50','2014-06-03 23:56:50','',0,'http://www.improv.org/?post_type=class&#038;p=996',0,'class','',0),(997,5,'2014-06-03 17:13:55','2014-06-04 00:13:55','<h1>Special Effects<br /> 1-Day; Aug. 22<br />Friday, 10:00 AM - 6:00 PM</h1>\r\n<p><em>This additional second section just added!</em></p>\r\n<p><strong>Friday, August 22nd, 2014<br /> Bayfront Theater, San Francisco</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Schedule:</strong> 10am-6pm, Friday, August 22 (with a 1hr lunch break)<br /> <strong>Class size:</strong> 12 students maximum<br /> <strong>Class length:</strong> 8 hours of class, 7 hours of instruction total<br /> <strong>Prerequisite:</strong> Foundation 3 and above.<br /><em>If you have any questions about your registration eligibility, please contact Regina Saisi at <a title=\"FS – Improv Singing: Rhythm and Style with David Norfleet and Patricia Pearson\" href=\"mailto:regina@improv.org\">regina@improv.org</a></em></p>\r\n<p>In this intensive, we will focus on using non-verbal offers to create scenes that have the special effects which often appear in movies. We\'ll practice using our body, voice, and imagination to create ghosts, gods, beasts, violence, cartoon-ish malleability, religious experiences, flight, telepathy, telekinesis, teleportation, phasers-on-stun, and anything else your brain can cook up.  Sign up, and add this interesting dimension to your improv play!</p>','Summer 2014 - Special Effects #2 with Ben Johnson (#08-1950)','','publish','open','open','','summer-2014-special-effects-section-2-with-ben-johnson','','','2014-06-04 10:32:47','2014-06-04 17:32:47','',0,'http://www.improv.org/?post_type=class&#038;p=997',0,'class','',0),(999,5,'2014-06-03 18:33:40','2014-06-04 01:33:40','<h1>Singing<br />Tuesdays, 7:00 - 10:00 PM</h1>\r\n<p><strong>July 8-29<br />Cubberley Community Center, Palo Alto</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"color: #000000;\"><strong>Schedule: </strong>4 sessions; once a week for four weeks <br /><strong>Class Time/Dates:</strong> 7-10 pm on Tuesdays July 8, 15, 22, and 29<br /><strong>Class size:</strong> 12 students maximum <strong><br />Class length: </strong>3 hours<strong> </strong>(12 hours total) <br /><strong>Prerequisite:</strong> Foundation 3 and above. If you have any questions about eligibility, please contact regina@improv.org.  </p>\r\n<p>This four-session workshop teaches the basic principles of how to create improvised solos, duets, and choruses based on suggestions. <br /><br />We break down the challenge of singing a song into its basics - breathing, ear and voice training, rhyme and rhythm exercises. </p>','Singing in Palo Alto - JRB (#07-1951)','','publish','open','open','','singing-in-palo-alto-jrb-07-1951','','','2014-06-03 18:35:44','2014-06-04 01:35:44','',0,'http://www.improv.org/?post_type=class&#038;p=999',0,'class','',0),(1004,5,'2014-06-05 16:03:15','2014-06-05 23:03:15','<p>Guest coach Maria Sommer.</p>','Maria Sommer','','publish','open','open','','maria-sommer','','','2014-06-05 16:03:15','2014-06-05 23:03:15','',0,'http://www.improv.org/?post_type=actors&#038;p=1004',9,'actors','',0),(1005,4,'2014-06-05 16:03:08','2014-06-05 23:03:08','<p>Guest coach TJ Weiss</p>','TJ Weiss','','publish','open','open','','tj-weiss','','','2014-06-05 16:05:31','2014-06-05 23:05:31','',0,'http://www.improv.org/?post_type=actors&#038;p=1005',10,'actors','',0),(1006,5,'2014-06-05 16:02:33','2014-06-05 23:02:33','','maria-236','','inherit','open','open','','maria-236','','','2014-06-05 16:02:33','2014-06-05 23:02:33','',1004,'http://www.improv.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/maria-236.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1007,4,'2014-06-05 16:02:46','2014-06-05 23:02:46','','tj-236','','inherit','open','open','','tj-236','','','2014-06-05 16:02:46','2014-06-05 23:02:46','',1005,'http://www.improv.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/tj-236.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1008,4,'2014-06-05 18:46:06','2014-06-06 01:46:06','','Email-logo-hilarious','','inherit','open','open','','email-logo-6-5-14','','','2014-06-05 18:46:06','2014-06-06 01:46:06','',0,'http://www.improv.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/Email-logo-6-5-14.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1009,4,'2014-06-05 18:47:51','2014-06-06 01:47:51','','full-signature','','inherit','open','open','','full-signature','','','2014-06-05 18:47:51','2014-06-06 01:47:51','',0,'http://www.improv.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/full-signature.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1012,4,'2014-06-08 20:18:45','2014-06-09 03:18:45','','warp-newsletter','','inhe