8:28','2015-01-19 22:28:28','',225,'http://www.improv.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/john3.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1604,7,'2015-01-21 11:50:44','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<h1><a href=\"http://bats.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/support_volunteer_company-players-05.jpg\"><img class=\"alignright size-full wp-image-757\" src=\"http://bats.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/support_volunteer_company-players-05.jpg\" alt=\"support_volunteer_company-players-05\" width=\"332\" height=\"221\" /></a>Volunteer at BATS</h1>\r\n<p>First off, we love, and need, our volunteers. <br /><strong>THANK YOU!!!</strong></p>\r\n<p>Volunteers are a critical part of the BATS Improv community and essential to our continued success as a nonprofit theatre. (You know we are a nonprofit, right?) Moreover, volunteering at BATS is fun and easy, gives you a behind-the-scenes look into live theatre, and is a great way to meet people who love improv as much as you do!</p>\r\n<p>Our volunteers come from all walks of life. Everyone is welcome. We have new volunteer opportunities every week, so no long-term commitment is required (though once you start, you might get hooked).</p>\r\n<p>Come, join the fun! Become a BATS volunteer and play a part in the only company in San Francisco that’s been blazing the improv trail since 1986. Here’s how.</p>\r\n<hr />\r\n<h3>Volunteer at a Show</h3>\r\n<p>As a Show Volunteer, you’ll see the show you support for free, plus get a free pass to come back and see another show on us. What’s more, you’ll get a unique behind-the-scenes experience at BATS Improv.</p>\r\n<p>Volunteer duties may include</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Ushering and greeting patrons</li>\r\n<li>Working BATS Cafe</li>\r\n<li>Operating the camera</li>\r\n<li>Scorekeeping during Theatresports<sup>TM</sup> tournaments</li>\r\n<li>House Manager support</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://eepurl.com/TbPn\" target=\"_blank\">Sign up for our Show Volunteer Mailing List »</a></p>\r\n<p>You’ll get information on upcoming shows plus a link where you can sign up to volunteer on specific dates. It takes less than a minute, and you can unsubscribe at any time.</p>\r\n<hr />\r\n<h3>Volunteer in the Office</h3>\r\n<p>Office Volunteers learn about the day-to-day operation of the biggest improvised theatre and improv school in the Bay Area. Volunteering in the BATS office is ideal for anyone thinking about a career in theatre or arts management.</p>\r\n<p>Volunteer duties may include</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Website: database management and data entry</li>\r\n<li>Communications: formatting, proofreading, image selection</li>\r\n<li>Development: database management, donor correspondence</li>\r\n<li>Administrative support</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>If you are interested in volunteering in the BATS office, please email <a href=\"mailto:BATS@improv.org\">BATS@improv.org</a> <br />or call <strong>(415) 474-6776</strong>.</p>','Volunteer (old version of page)','','draft','open','open','','','','','2015-01-21 11:50:44','2015-01-21 19:50:44','',15,'http://www.improv.org/?page_id=1604',14,'page','',0),(1607,2,'2015-01-22 10:13:41','2015-01-22 18:13:41','','Thirteenth Show','','publish','closed','closed','','acf_thirteenth-show','','','2015-01-22 10:13:41','2015-01-22 18:13:41','',0,'http://www.improv.org/?post_type=acf&#038;p=1607',0,'acf','',0),(1610,7,'2015-01-26 18:49:33','2015-01-27 02:49:33','<h1><img class=\"alignright wp-image-772 size-medium\" style=\"margin-right: 10px;\" src=\"http://www.improv.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/school_Youth-3-300x173.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"173\" /><strong>Educational Outreach</strong></h1>\r\n<p>The BATS Educational Outreach Program in the San Francisco Bay Area offers workshops for students and educators in grades K-12. Bring us to your classroom, after-school program, or professional development day, or take one of our education-focused courses. </p>\r\n<h3><strong><br />Why improv in schools?</strong></h3>\r\n<p>BATS Educational Outreach offers improvisation-based workshops for students that enhance classroom instruction and tie into CA and National curriculum standards. Improvisation is a highly effective tool for developing skills such as <strong>listening, team building, idea generation, brainstorming, literacy, communication, problem solving, social integration and empathy</strong>. It is active, student-centered learning that supports the development of critical thinking and multiple intelligences. BATS\' specific brand of improvisation offers both techniques in short games and exercises and in longform storytelling and narrative that can be adapted to large or small groups on their feet or in their desks.</p>\r\n<p><strong>We believe that humans are most receptive to learning when they’re enjoying themselves.</strong> Our improv professionals create engaging, no-pressure learning environments that bring out the best in your students and teachers. The flexibility of improvisation and theater allows us to work in just about any environment and with any learning level.</p>\r\n<p><em>See below for some of our offerings.  Contact us at <a href=\"mailto:education@improv.org\">education@improv.org</a> for more information.</em></p>\r\n<hr />\r\n<h1><strong>Artists in Residence</strong></h1>\r\n<p>The goal of our residencies is to provide on-going quality instruction for students while modeling improvisational tools for educators to continue to use in the classroom after the residency is over. Goals of residency may include, but are not limited to, developing literacy skills, exploring curriculum content areas, teaching drama and improvisation skills, or creating and performing an original presentation.</p>\r\n<p>Artist in Residence programs offer the integration of our teaching artists into your environment with customization to your specific needs. Bring us in for a few days or several weeks depending upon your budget, learning goals, and needs. Short term &amp; long term residencies can be applied to single classrooms or across groups of students.</p>\r\n<p><em>Examples of Residency Curricular Focus: </em></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Shakespeare</li>\r\n<li>The McCarthy Era (Process Drama)</li>\r\n<li>Greek Tragedy Exploration</li>\r\n<li>Anti-Bullying</li>\r\n<li>Storytelling for Literacy</li>\r\n<li>Our History Ourselves</li>\r\n<li>Character Counts / Life-skills</li>\r\n<li>Language Arts / Storytelling</li>\r\n<li>Historical Event or Period (Process Drama)</li>\r\n<li>Self-Expression and Performance</li>\r\n<li>Problem Solving (Often Science Based)</li>\r\n<li>Project Based Learning across disciplines</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><em>Note: The ideal area for our Artist in Residence programs is an open space like a Multi Purpose Room or theatre, though most exercises can easily be adapted to a classroom. Class size is limited per teaching artist. Classroom teacher or supervising adult must remain in the room with our Teaching Artists at all times.</em></p>\r\n<hr />\r\n<h1><strong>Workshops</strong></h1>\r\n<p>While our residencies are intended to be longer term and provide depth of learning, the goal of our workshops is to provide short-term or one-off instruction for students and teachers. These are often more light-hearted and provide introductory level goals that may include, but are not limited to, basic literacy and storytelling skills, introductory drama and improvisation skills, or teambuilding and lifeskills.</p>\r\n<p>Our workshops offer a brief, invigorating integration of our teaching artists into your environment with customization to your specific needs. Bring us in for a few hours or few days depending upon your budget, learning goals, and needs. Workshops can be applied to single classrooms or across groups of students.</p>\r\n<p><em>Examples of Workshop Curricular Focus: </em></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Introduction to Shakespeare (language &amp; themes)</li>\r\n<li>Storytelling Techniques</li>\r\n<li>Brainstorming</li>\r\n<li>Think Like a Scientist/Historian</li>\r\n<li>Teambuilding</li>\r\n<li>To Improv</li>\r\n<li>Tackling Stage Fright</li>\r\n<li>Acting The Story/Becoming the Characters</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><em>Note: The ideal area for our workshops is an open space like a Multi Purpose Room or theatre, though most exercises can easily be adapted to a classroom. Class size is limited per teaching artist. Classroom teacher or supervising adult must remain in the room with our Teaching Artists at all times. </em></p>\r\n<hr />\r\n<h1><strong>Professional Development</strong></h1>\r\n<p>BATS’ customized Professional Development is the antidote for bad PowerPoint presentations, awkward icebreaker games, and ironically long-winded sage on the stage speeches about the benefits of brevity in the classroom. Inspired by your school’s needs and current PD focus, our improv professionals will create a personalized experience that transforms the notoriously long day into an engaging experience with immediately useable classroom exercises. </p>\r\n<p>We’ll work with you to develop the perfect program for your group of educators, be it teambuilding or integration of National Standards. Whatever the theme, the work is a journey that brings people together through shared fun, laughter, and creativity and sneaks in those curricular links in ways that feel empowering, invigorating, and inspiring to teachers of all experience levels. On-your-feet, usable, doable, easily repeatable exercises.  Tools for teachers of any grade, subject, or learning level. PD that actually models what it\'s teaching &amp; is immediately applicable to your classroom!</p>\r\n<p><em>Benefits of BATS Professional Development: </em></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Active engaged learning at its best applicable to all students - including special needs, GATE, ESL.   </li>\r\n<li>Modeling &amp; implementation of multiple-learning styles approach that is fun</li>\r\n<li>Teaching artists consistently modeling the teaching techniques that teacher can then immediately modify &amp; imitate in their classroom</li>\r\n<li>Large, small, and individual guided practice with Teaching Artists</li>\r\n<li>These Professional development skills are immediately usable in the classroom</li>\r\n<li>Effortlessly tie into specific WASC, Common Core, CA State Standards or other requirements</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<hr />\r\n<h1><strong> Additional Benefits or Add Ons</strong></h1>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Curriculum planning meeting(s) with teachers or admins.</li>\r\n<li>Customizable programs specific to your school, learning goals, finances, and student population</li>\r\n<li>1- 2 Trained artists per class  (based on group size, program needs, and teaching artist availability)</li>\r\n<li>Pre &amp; Post-class supplemental/supporting materials highlighting incorporation of CA Standards, life-skills, etc.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<hr />\r\n<h1><strong>Pricing</strong></h1>\r\n<p>All of our Educational Outreach Programs are customized, and pricing may be impacted by travel, facility use, material preparation, and/or grant availability. Please contact <em><a href=\"mailto:education@improv.org\">education@improv.org</a></em> for more information.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','Educational Outreach Program','','publish','open','open','','education','','','2015-11-10 19:56:33','2015-11-11 03:56:33','',13,'http://www.improv.org/?page_id=1610',3,'page','',0),(1611,4,'2015-01-27 16:31:56','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<p>Each night of DuoProv, three pairs of improvisers put it all on the line by playing as a team of two - that’s right only two players per team! Witness our dauntless improvisers as they face the challenge of taking BATS stage with only their imaginations to rely on. What characters will be created? What stories will unfold? Join us and find out! As each Duo digs, the unexpected will happen.</p>\r\n<p><em><span style=\"color: #d9541e;\"><a style=\"color: #d9541e;\" title=\"Group Tickets\" href=\"http://www.improv.org/shows/groups/\"><strong>Group tickets</strong> start at just $14 each for groups of 10+</a><br /><a style=\"color: #d9541e;\" title=\"Gift Certificates\" href=\"http://www.improv.org/shows/gift-certificates/\">You can also give this show as a gift with a </a><a style=\"color: #d9541e;\" title=\"Gift Certificates\" href=\"http://www.improv.org/shows/gift-certificates/\"><strong>BATS Gift Certific</strong><strong>ate</strong>.</a> <strong><br /></strong></span></em></p>','DuoProv','','draft','open','open','','','','','2015-01-27 16:31:56','0000-00-00 00:00:00','',0,'http://www.improv.org/?post_type=friday&p=1611',8,'friday','',0),(1613,5,'2015-01-28 13:42:30','2015-01-28 21:42:30','<h1>Performance Workshop 3 - <br />Elements of Long Form<br />    Sundays, <br />10:00 AM - 6:00 PM for 3 weeks<br />2:30 PM - 5:30 PM for 1 week</h1>\r\n<p><strong>March 1 - March 22, 2015<br />Bayfront Theater, San Francisco<br /> </strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"color: #000000;\"><strong>Schedule:</strong> 4 sessions and 1 performance<br /><strong>Class Time/Dates: </strong>10am-6pm, with a one-hour lunch break from 1:30-2:30pm on Sundays March 1, 8, and 15. <br />2:30-5:30pm on Sunday, March 22.<br /><strong>Performance: </strong>Sunday, March 22, 6pm at the Bayfront Theater<br /><strong>Class size:</strong> 10 students maximum <strong><br />Class length: </strong>7 hours for 3 weeks and 3 hours on 1 week (24 hours total of instruction)<br /><strong>Prerequisite: </strong>Performance Workshop 1 and 2 or coach/dean approval. Contact regina@improv.org with any eligibility questions.<em><br /> </em></p>\r\n<p>This workshop condenses the full content of our 8-week Performance Workshop 3 series into 4 sessions with an intensive schedule. You\'ll dive into the work and play of learning long-form skills in three 7-hour sessions and one 3-hour session. The Performance Workshop 3: Elements of Long Form, prepares you for your first Long-Form performance in front of an audience by breaking down and covering these different core elements of performance: </p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Taking your time and paying attention</li>\r\n<li>Narrative, and establishing a strong foundation</li>\r\n<li>Acting</li>\r\n<li>Improvising in genre</li>\r\n<li>Transitions between scenes</li>\r\n<li>Ensemble acting</li>\r\n<li>Building locations and maintaining a space object world</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>This class will qualify you to be considered for more advanced work as it will give you a grounding in the essential elements of Long-Form improvisation as BATS practices it.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','Performance - Performance Workshop 3 (ELF) with Dave Dennison & Regina Saisi (#15-03-2074)','','publish','open','open','','performance-performance-workshop-3-elf-with-dave-dennison-regina-saisi-15-03-2074','','','2015-01-28 13:45:04','2015-01-28 21:45:04','',0,'http://www.improv.org/?post_type=class&#038;p=1613',0,'class','',0),(1615,5,'2015-01-28 14:20:31','2015-01-28 22:20:31','<h1>Intro to Improv in the Mission<br />Tuesday, 7:00 - 10:00 PM</h1>\r\n<p><strong>February 10, 2015<br />Studio 210, San Francisco (the Mission)</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Schedule</strong>: One session<br /> <strong>Class date:</strong> February 10th<br /> <strong>Class length</strong>: 3 hours<br /> <strong>Tuition</strong>: $45<br /> <strong>Prerequisite:</strong> None - everyone is welcome!</p>','I - Intro to Improv with Chris Sams at 210 (#15-02-2075)','','publish','open','open','','i-intro-to-improv-with-chris-sams-at-210-15-02-2075','','','2015-01-28 14:20:31','2015-01-28 22:20:31','',0,'http://www.improv.org/?post_type=class&#038;p=1615',0,'class','',0),(1617,4,'2015-01-29 11:59:33','2015-01-29 19:59:33','','theatresports-Jan30','','inherit','open','open','','theatresports-jan30','','','2015-01-29 11:59:33','2015-01-29 19:59:33','',0,'http://www.improv.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/theatresports-Jan30.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1618,4,'2015-01-29 12:05:12','2015-01-29 20:05:12','','super-scene-close','','inherit','open','open','','super-scene-close','','','2015-01-29 12:05